":"Chagford, Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Prouz","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Northumberland and Durham): nickname for a vain or haughtyman, from Middle English <i>prod</i>, <i>prud</i> ‘proud’ (late OldEnglish <i>prūd</i>, from the oblique form of Old French<i>proz</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Proudman","meanings":["English (northwest Midlands):","nickname from Middle English <i>proud</i> ‘proud, haughty, arrogant’ + <i>man</i>. Compare   Proud  ,   Proudfoot  .","(of Norman origin): nickname from Old French <i>prud'homme</i> ‘honest, upright man’."]},{"name":"Prout","meanings":["English (mainly Cornwall): variant of   Proud  .","French: variant of   Provost   ‘provost’."]},{"name":"Prude","meanings":["English: perhaps a variant of   Proud  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Prouz was born in 1342, in Chagford, Devon, England, United Kingdom, his father, William le Prouz, was 49 and his mother, Elena de Ponte, was 42. He had at least 1 son with Eustacia de Wadscotte."},"et":{"1342–":"1342–Surnud","1316–1406":"1316–1406","1342–Male":"1342–Surnud","1337–1391":"1337–1391","1368–1447":"1368–1447","1